Incandescent bulbs are being phased out in many countries due to their low energy efficiency.
Less than 3% of the input energy is converted into usable light.
Nearly all of the input energy ends up as heat that, in warm climates, must then be removed from the building by ventilation or air conditioning, often resulting in more energy consumption.
In colder climates where heating and lighting is required during the cold and dark winter months, the heat byproduct has at least some value.
